00:45:49.450 --> 00:45:51.660
event, which is that conflict.

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:54.610
And so if you can get your
audience nodding in agreement,

00:45:54.610 --> 00:45:56.720
going yeah, yeah, that's
the problem I have.

00:45:56.720 --> 00:45:58.740
I have that problem.

00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:01.070
Then you're going to hook them.

00:46:01.070 --> 00:46:02.700
That's what we call the hook.

00:46:02.700 --> 00:46:04.720
Just like the chorus
in "Cheerleader."

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:06.820
That's what we call the hook.

00:46:06.820 --> 00:46:09.680
It works remarkably
well, remarkably well.

00:46:09.680 --> 00:46:11.120
I cannot tell you
over the years,

00:46:11.120 --> 00:46:14.590
of how many business
presentations I've either seen

00:46:14.590 --> 00:46:19.720
or I've worked with at a lot
of major companies-- LinkedIn,

00:46:19.720 --> 00:46:24.470
Microsoft, SanDisk,
Intel, many--

00:46:24.470 --> 00:46:28.880
where when we create something
like this and then we go back

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:31.260
and we see what was the
most memorable part of that

00:46:31.260 --> 00:46:34.380
presentation, what
resonated with people.

00:46:34.380 --> 00:46:37.070
People come back,
like, two years later

00:46:37.070 --> 00:46:39.570
at the same conference
and tell the executive,

00:46:39.570 --> 00:46:41.470
I liked that part
in that presentation

00:46:41.470 --> 00:46:42.640
you gave two years ago.

00:46:42.640 --> 00:46:44.680
It's always the story.

00:46:44.680 --> 00:46:45.860
Always the story.

00:46:45.860 --> 00:46:49.761
Nobody ever remembers oh
yeah, I loved that slide 32.

00:46:49.761 --> 00:46:50.260
Excellent.

00:46:50.260 --> 00:46:51.220
That was great.

00:46:51.220 --> 00:46:53.360
Yeah, and the chart on slide 32?

00:46:53.360 --> 00:46:54.410
Unbelievable.

00:46:54.410 --> 00:46:57.260
But they always remember
the story, always.

00:46:57.260 --> 00:46:59.320
That's why I'm getting
into this idea, where

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:01.260
I am very emphatic about it.

00:47:01.260 --> 00:47:03.740
I'm saying, this is the hook.

00:47:03.740 --> 00:47:06.340
A songwriter knows what works.

00:47:06.340 --> 00:47:09.380
That's why he can keep
turning out hit after hit.

00:47:09.380 --> 00:47:10.760
We know what works too.

00:47:10.760 --> 00:47:14.492
We know what works when you're
delivering a presentation.

00:47:14.492 --> 00:47:16.200
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about telling

00:47:16.200 --> 00:47:17.070
personal stories--

00:47:17.070 --> 00:47:17.930
CARMINE GALLO: Yes.

00:47:17.930 --> 00:47:20.260
Now, your father is a
data scientist, right?

00:47:20.260 --> 00:47:21.220
AUDIENCE: Computer
science professor.

00:47:21.220 --> 00:47:22.050
CARMINE GALLO: Computer science.

00:47:22.050 --> 00:47:22.970
And he tells stories?

00:47:22.970 --> 00:47:23.720
AUDIENCE: He does.

00:47:23.720 --> 00:47:24.165
CARMINE GALLO: I love it.

00:47:24.165 --> 00:47:24.360
I love that.

00:47:24.360 --> 00:47:25.260
AUDIENCE: Telling
stories in the classroom

00:47:25.260 --> 00:47:26.301
is very important to him.

00:47:26.301 --> 00:47:27.610
CARMINE GALLO: Great.

00:47:27.610 --> 00:47:30.193
AUDIENCE: I've noticed that when
people tell personal stories,

00:47:30.193 --> 00:47:32.570
they generally fall
into one of two frames.

00:47:32.570 --> 00:47:34.950
There's the
this-is-how-I'm-special angle.

00:47:34.950 --> 00:47:38.640
And then there's the
this-is-how-we're-alike angle.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:41.860
Can you comment on which
of those-- is one of them

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:42.780
superior to the other?

00:47:42.780 --> 00:47:44.970
Do they both have a place?

00:47:44.970 --> 00:47:46.820
CARMINE GALLO: Well,
let's not get too

00:47:46.820 --> 00:47:48.740
hung up on the personal stories.

00:47:48.740 --> 00:47:49.110
AUDIENCE: I guess any stories?

00:47:49.110 --> 00:47:50.070
CARMINE GALLO: Yeah.

00:47:50.070 --> 00:47:55.840
Because for TED, the personal
stories work pretty well.

00:47:55.840 --> 00:47:58.260
Because it is a more
intimate environment.

00:47:58.260 --> 00:48:01.030
In business, I like
the case studies.

00:48:01.030 --> 00:48:05.140
You know, real stories of
real people who are helped

00:48:05.140 --> 00:48:09.820
or whose world is made better
by your idea, by your service.

00:48:09.820 --> 00:48:12.760
Those are the stories
that resonate in business.

00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:15.780
And very few business
presentations-- at least

00:48:15.780 --> 00:48:18.410
that I see- are
heavy in narrative.

00:48:18.410 --> 00:48:19.910
They don't tell those stories.

00:48:19.910 --> 00:48:23.320
It's all fact without being
supported by the stories.

00:48:23.320 --> 00:48:25.220
You know who's really
good at this now,

00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:26.890
is Bill and Melinda Gates.

00:48:26.890 --> 00:48:30.320
They're fantastic
storytellers now.

00:48:30.320 --> 00:48:34.070
Like, every time they have the
new Gates newsletter, which

00:48:34.070 --> 00:48:36.390
comes out every year and
talks about their philanthropy

00:48:36.390 --> 00:48:40.640
efforts, Melinda is a better
storyteller than Bill.

00:48:40.640 --> 00:48:42.430
Bill's still a little factual.

00:48:42.430 --> 00:48:43.640
He's very simple though.

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:44.760
He does a good job.

00:48:44.760 --> 00:48:46.950
But Melinda likes
going into the stories.

00:48:46.950 --> 00:48:49.140
So she uses the data.

00:48:49.140 --> 00:48:52.800
But she always starts with
very personal stories.

00:48:52.800 --> 00:48:54.490
And sometimes they're personal.

00:48:54.490 --> 00:48:56.880
But they're more
about other people.

00:48:56.880 --> 00:48:59.490
It's more of a personal
experience she had.

00:48:59.490 --> 00:49:03.700
But let me tell you about a
woman in this part of Africa

00:49:03.700 --> 00:49:06.610
who I spent a few days with,
and her and her family.

00:49:06.610 --> 00:49:08.910
So it's kind of about
Melinda, but not really.

00:49:08.910 --> 00:49:11.610
She kind of shifts it off and
talks about the other person.

00:49:11.610 --> 00:49:19.550
So I think the case studies, but
inserting yourself into a case

00:49:19.550 --> 00:49:20.990
study is very powerful.

00:49:20.990 --> 00:49:23.890
AUDIENCE: Do you have any advice
on how to use storytelling

00:49:23.890 --> 00:49:28.010
in job interviews when
you have very little time,

00:49:28.010 --> 00:49:30.759
and you have to kind
of sell yourself?

00:49:30.759 --> 00:49:31.550
CARMINE GALLO: Yes.

00:49:31.550 --> 00:49:34.530
You have to do it
in job interviews.

00:49:34.530 --> 00:49:37.090
I have so many
interesting stories

00:49:37.090 --> 00:49:39.050
of people who have emailed me.

00:49:39.050 --> 00:49:41.530
One young man emailed me
not too long ago, just

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:44.675
a few months ago, working at
a startup in San Francisco.

00:49:48.342 --> 00:49:49.550
I'm sure you're all familiar.

00:49:49.550 --> 00:49:52.220
They do the coding
classes now, right?

00:49:52.220 --> 00:49:53.640
Those coding programs.

00:49:53.640 --> 00:49:53.870
DAVE MARX: The boot camps.

00:49:53.870 --> 00:49:55.369
CARMINE GALLO: Yeah,
the boot camps.

00:49:55.369 --> 00:49:58.070
So that was his first
coding boot camp.

00:49:58.070 --> 00:50:01.140
And so he didn't have a lot
of technical experience.

00:50:01.140 --> 00:50:03.680
But he was a really
good communicator.

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:06.010
He studied the science of story.

00:50:06.010 --> 00:50:07.470
And how to tell better stories.

00:50:07.470 --> 00:50:09.860
So he walked into an interview.

00:50:09.860 --> 00:50:13.050
And he told stories
about his previous job,

00:50:13.050 --> 00:50:16.700
of where they had a
particular problem.

00:50:16.700 --> 00:50:19.800
And he told those stories of
how he overcame those problems.

00:50:19.800 --> 00:50:23.780
And then he applied what he
had learned to that company,

00:50:23.780 --> 00:50:25.840
and what he had learned
about this new company.

00:50:25.840 --> 00:50:27.530
So that doesn't take long.

00:50:27.530 --> 00:50:30.450
Even in a 15-minute
job interview,

00:50:30.450 --> 00:50:32.260
that took about two minutes.

00:50:32.260 --> 00:50:34.470
But here's the
end of that story.

00:50:34.470 --> 00:50:36.430
Here's the conclusion.

00:50:36.430 --> 00:50:39.805
The reason why the young
man emailed me, he said,

00:50:39.805 --> 00:50:41.180
Carmine, you
wouldn't believe it.

00:50:41.180 --> 00:50:42.640
I doubled my salary.

00:50:42.640 --> 00:50:44.616
They hired me two days later.

00:50:44.616 --> 00:50:45.740
He interviewed on a Friday.

00:50:45.740 --> 00:50:47.110
They hired him on a Monday.

00:50:47.110 --> 00:50:48.470
Doubled my salary.

00:50:48.470 --> 00:50:50.660
And they told them
specifically, you

00:50:50.660 --> 00:50:52.410
don't have the
technical experience.

00:50:52.410 --> 00:50:54.434
Because you just took
this one coding class.

00:50:54.434 --> 00:50:55.850
There are plenty
of job candidates

00:50:55.850 --> 00:50:58.760
who have more technical
experience than you do.

00:50:58.760 --> 00:51:02.470
But nobody could
communicate our story,

00:51:02.470 --> 00:51:05.570
our company story,
as well as you can.

00:51:05.570 --> 00:51:09.360
So to me, what we just
talked about, that's big.

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:11.862
This is really important
for career advancement.

00:51:11.862 --> 00:51:12.820
Yeah, really important.

00:51:12.820 --> 00:51:14.390
Thanks for asking.

00:51:14.390 --> 00:51:16.030
Well, look, I'll be around.

00:51:16.030 --> 00:51:20.272
And I'd love to sign some books
and meet you, if you'd like.

00:51:20.272 --> 00:51:20.980
Great, thank you.

00:51:20.980 --> 00:51:21.580
DAVE MARX: One more round
of applause for Carmine.

00:51:21.580 --> 00:51:21.880
CARMINE GALLO: Thank you.

00:51:21.880 --> 00:51:22.546
Yeah, thank you.

00:51:22.546 --> 00:51:24.030
[APPLAUSE]

